 equipped with a binary operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
magma
\series default
, and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
semigroup 
\series default
if the binary operation is 
\series bold
associative
\series default
; that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\star y)\star z=x\star(y\star z)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
monoid 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is a semigroup and there exists a 
\series bold
left 
\series default
and 
\series bold
right inverse
\series default
 
\series bold
element
\series default
; that is, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $e,e'\in X$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e\star x=x=x\star e'
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we automatically have 
\begin_inset Formula $e=e'$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e' & =e\star e'\\
 & =e.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For this reason, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

