First we show that any element in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a product of disjoint cycles.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall describe an algorithm which expresses 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 as a product of disjoint cycles.
 In the first step of the algorithm, choose any 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1,1}\in[n]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the least nonnegative integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{k_{1}}(a_{1,1})=a_{1,1}$
\end_inset

.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1,i_{1}}=\sigma^{i_{1}-1}(a_{1,1})$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i_{1}\leq k_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k_{1}\leq n$
\end_inset

 by the pigeonhole principle.
 Also observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1,i_{1}}\neq a_{1,i_{1}'}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}\neq i_{1}'$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1,i_{1}}=a_{1,i_{1}'}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i_{1}<i_{1}'\leq k_{1}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma^{i_{1}'-i_{1}}(a_{1,1}) & =\sigma^{i_{1}'}\sigma^{-i_{1}}(a_{1,1})\\
 & =\sigma^{-i_{1}}\sigma^{i_{1}'}(a_{1,1})\\
 & =\sigma^{-i_{1}}(a_{1,i_{1}'})\\
 & =\sigma^{-i_{1}}(a_{1,i_{1}})\\
 & =a_{1,1},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which would contradict the minimality of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}'-i_{1}<k_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So if we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}=(a_{1,1}\cdots a_{1,k_{1}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}=\tau_{1}^{-1}\sigma$
\end_inset

, then we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\tau_{1}\sigma_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
