\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(u)=(\psi_{\lambda}(u))
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M_{i}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\pi_{\lambda}\psi)(u) & =\pi_{\lambda}(\psi(u))\\
 & =\pi_{\lambda}((\psi_{\lambda}(u))\\
 & =\psi_{\lambda}(u).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\lambda}\psi=\psi_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

